Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is fine-tuning?
AI Response

Fine-tuning updates a pre-trained model's weights on a smaller, task-specific dataset. It is more efficient than
training from scratch and achieves strong performance with limited data.

Example 1.2

User

What is an RNN?
AI Response

A Recurrent Neural Network processes sequential data with loops allowing information to persist. LSTMs and
GRUs are variants that address the vanishing gradient problem.

Example 1.3

User

What is PCA?
AI Response

Principal Component Analysis reduces dimensionality by transforming data to axes of greatest variance. It
reduces noise, speeds up training, and helps visualize high-dimensional data.

Example 1.4

User

What is word embedding?
AI Response

Word embeddings map words to dense vectors where similar words are nearby. Word2Vec, GloVe, and
FastText are popular methods, used as NLP model input features.

Example 1.5

User

What is a decision tree?
AI Response

A decision tree splits data by feature values at internal nodes, with leaves representing predictions. They are
interpretable but prone to overfitting without pruning.

Example 1.6

User

What is precision vs recall?
AI Response

Precision is correct positive predictions / all positive predictions. Recall is correct positive predictions / all
actual positives. F1 score harmonically balances both.

Example 1.7

User

What is reinforcement learning?
AI Response



Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by interacting with an environment and receiving
rewards or penalties, aiming to maximize cumulative reward over time.

Example 1.8

User

What is an epoch?
AI Response

An epoch is one full pass through the entire training dataset. Multiple epochs are used, and the number is a
key hyperparameter affecting model convergence.

Example 1.9

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.10

User

What is a GAN?
AI Response

A Generative Adversarial Network pits a generator (creates fake data) against a discriminator (identifies
fakes), training each other until the generator produces realistic data.



